This French-language article from Kompozite explores the concept of CO2 equivalent (CO2e), a critical measurement unit for greenhouse gas emissions. The piece likely explains how CO2e helps standardize and compare different types of greenhouse gases by converting their global warming potential to a common scale based on carbon dioxide. By using this unified metric, researchers, policymakers, and organizations can more accurately assess and communicate the environmental impact of various emissions sources. The article appears to provide insights into why CO2e is important for understanding climate change, how different gases contribute to global warming, and potentially offers guidance on measuring and reducing carbon footprints across different sectors and activities.
